            <table align="center" border="0" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" class="containermaster_blue">
             <tr>
              <td>
               <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%">

                 <td nowrap="" valign="middle" width="100%">
                  <span class="Head" id="dnn_ctr1358_dnnTITLE_lblTitle">
                   The First Thanksgivingukkah
                  </span>
                 </td>
                 <td nowrap="" valign="middle">
                  <a href="javascript:__doPostBack('dnn$ctr1358$dnnVISIBILITY$cmdVisibility','')" id="dnn_ctr1358_dnnVISIBILITY_cmdVisibility" title="Minimize">
                   <img alt="Minimize" border="0" id="dnn_ctr1358_dnnVISIBILITY_imgVisibility" src="/images/min.gif" title="Minimize"/>
                  </a>

                </tr>
               </table>
               <hr class="containermaster_blue"/>
              </td>
             </tr>
             <tr>
              <td align="left" id="dnn_ctr1358_ContentPane">
               <!-- Start_Module_1358 -->
               <div id="dnn_ctr1358_ModuleContent">
                <span class="Normal" id="dnn_ctr1358_HtmlModule_lblContent">
                 <img alt="" height="267" src="/Portals/0/thankgivinukkah.jpg" width="400"/>
                 <br/>
                 <br/>
                 Archaeologists and Judaeophile ethnographers debate the origins of Thanksgivingukkah to this day. Cave paintings found near Qumran appear to include Roast Turkey recipes, depictions of an empty rock for Elijah and various complaints about Mothers-in-law.
                 <br/>
                 <br/>
                 <img alt="" height="425" src="/Portals/0/Hebrew Gothic.jpg" width="350"/>
                 <br/>
                 Whatever its mythic origins, Thanksgivingukkah has had a lasting place in Jewish culture throughout the Diaspora. Most early Thanksgivingukkahs were based on Sephardic traditions, but the festival reportedly "Went all ghetto" in the medieval period.
                 <br/>
                 <br/>
                 <img alt="" height="251" src="/Portals/0/th1.jpg" width="349"/>
                 <br/>
                 Early stories tell of the Israelites landing on El Al chartered vessel on the shores of Canaan after tossing at see for forty days and nights fleeing Pharoah's navy. The early Israelites were thankful just for being alive after forty days of prepackaged kosher meals.
                 <br/>
                 <br/>
                 <img alt="" height="168" src="/Portals/0/th2.jpg" width="300"/>
                 <br/>
                 <br/>
                 Early relations with the Canaanites were strained on suspicion that the Israelites had intentions of taking over the land. But Moses promised, "No, we totally are not trying to take your land, honest!" This heartfelt promise was the beginning of a long period of warm relations between the two groups, who lived together peacefully ever after.
                 <br/>
                 <br/>
                 <img alt="" height="241" src="/Portals/0/th3.jpg" width="350"/>
                 <br/>
                 <br/>
                 The two parties feasted and shared each other's delicacies. When the food ran low, Moses ran out for Chinese. Before leaving he warned, "Don't start worshipping idols in my absence or anything like that." But when he returned there was much idol worship going on, as well as meat and dairy dishes being served. A lot of violence ensued, leading the Canaanites to wonder, "Did we land on Mount Zion, or did Mount Zion land on us?"
                 <br/>
                 <br/>
                 <img alt="" height="345" src="/Portals/0/th4.jpg" width="400"/>
                 <br/>
                 Eventually calm was restored by someone's overbearing yet kind hearted grandmother, and the feasting resumed. Unfortuneately there was only enough gravy in the gravy boat for one day of feasting. But lo and behold the gravy lasted for eight days. And there were dreidel games and chocolate gilt for the children as well as much watching of football. And this is the true story of the very first Thanksgivingukkah.
                </span>
                <!-- End_Module_1358 -->
